\(\renewcommand{\hat}[1]{\widehat{#1}}\)

09_calculate_z_from_sample_mean


  1. Question

    This question provides \(\mu\), \(\sigma\), \(n\), and \(\bar{x}\). You will characterize the sampling distribution by finding the standard error, calculate the standard score, determine the percentile rank (expressed as a decimal), and translate the score into a rating (see below).

    Population

    When Archie practices archery, each arrow has the same probability distribution (see i.i.d). This means her skill is constant, there is no hot-hand effect, and there is no maturity of chances.

    Over many months, Archie has shot ten thousand arrows (their positions are shown below as dots).


    From those many arrows, Archie has determined an accurate probability distribution (of the points scored by an arrow).


    Archie has determined her arrows population mean and population standard deviation. \[\mu=7.12\] \[\sigma=2.04 \]

    Sampling distribution

    Each day, Archie shoots 96 arrows (\(n=96\)) and determines that days mean score. A mean of 10 would be a perfect day. We can treat each days mean as a random variable with its own probability distribution: a sampling distribution. We wish to characterize this sampling distribution. From the central limit theorem, we know the sampling distribution is approximately normal; however, we need to calculate the parameters: the mean and the standard error.

    Mean of the sampling distribution

    The sampling distributions mean is simply equal to the population mean. \[\text{expected mean} = \mu \]

    • What is the sampling distributions mean?

    Standard error (standard deviation of sampling distribution)

    The standard error of a mean is the quotient of the population standard deviation and the square root of the sample size. \[\text{standard error of mean} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\] This standard error is the standard deviation of the sampling distribution.

    • What is the standard error of the sampling distribution?

    Sample

    Today, Archies mean score is 7.073 points (\(\bar{x} = 7.073\)).


    Standard score

    Archie would like to know how well she did today. She wants you to calculate a standard score (a \(z\) score). To calculate the standard score of a sample mean, you can use the following formula. \[z = \frac{\bar x - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\]

    • What is the \(z\) score?

    Cumulative probability (percentile rank)

    Archie would like to know the probability that tomorrow she shoots worse than today. To estimate this, report the cumulative probability associated with the \(z\)-score you calculated. This can be done with a \(z\) table, pnorm function in R, NORM.DIST function in a spreadsheet, or with other standard normal tools.

    Remember, since we are using a \(z\) score, the normal distribution parameters are mean=0 and sd=1.

    • What is the probability that Archie shoots worse tomorrow?

    Rating

    Archie would like a rating for her days performance. You decide to use the following scale and that if \(z\) is on a boundary, Archie will be given the higher rating.

    \(z\) interval rating
    \(-\infty\) to -1.51 F
    -1.5 to -0.51 D
    -0.5 to 0.49 C
    0.5 to 1.49 B
    1.5 to \(\infty\) A


    • Determine Archies rating:


    Solution

    The sampling distribution is approximately normal with mean 7.12 and standard error 0.208.

    \[\mathrm{SE} ~=~ \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} ~=~\frac{2.04}{\sqrt{96}} ~\approx~ 0.208\]

    The \(z\) score is found with the given formula.

    \[z ~=~ \frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{\mathrm{SE}} ~=~ \frac{7.073-7.12}{0.208} ~\approx~ -0.23\]

    The sampling distribution can be visualized, along with todays mean (7.073) highlighted in red. The cumulative probability is the sum of the probabilities of scores less than (or equal) 7.073. Thus, the area highlighted in blue represents the cumulative probability.


    To find the cumulative probability using a spreadsheet, you can use =NORM.DIST(-0.2257373,0,1,TRUE). \[P(Z\le -0.2257373) ~=~ 0.4107\]

    By comparing the \(z\) score to the grade chart, you find the proper rating is C.

    exsolution: 10000|00001|00010|01000|00100

    Archie would like to know the probability that tomorrow she shoots worse than today. To estimate this, report the cumulative probability associated with the \(z\)-score you calculated. This can be done with a \(z\) table, pnorm function in R, NORM.DIST function in a spreadsheet, or with other standard normal tools.

    Remember, since we are using a \(z\) score, the normal distribution parameters are mean=0 and sd=1.

    • What is the probability that Archie shoots worse tomorrow?

    Rating

    Archie would like a rating for her days performance. You decide to use the following scale and that if \(z\) is on a boundary, Archie will be given the higher rating.

    \(z\) interval rating
    \(-\infty\) to -1.51 F
    -1.5 to -0.51 D
    -0.5 to 0.49 C
    0.5 to 1.49 B
    1.5 to \(\infty\) A


    • Determine Archies rating:


    Solution

    The sampling distribution is approximately normal with mean 7.31 and standard error 0.218.

    \[\mathrm{SE} ~=~ \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} ~=~\frac{1.85}{\sqrt{72}} ~\approx~ 0.218\]

    The \(z\) score is found with the given formula.

    \[z ~=~ \frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{\mathrm{SE}} ~=~ \frac{7.583-7.31}{0.218} ~\approx~ 1.25\]

    The sampling distribution can be visualized, along with todays mean (7.583) highlighted in red. The cumulative probability is the sum of the probabilities of scores less than (or equal) 7.583. Thus, the area highlighted in blue represents the cumulative probability.


    To find the cumulative probability using a spreadsheet, you can use =NORM.DIST(1.2521523,0,1,TRUE). \[P(Z\le 1.2521523) ~=~ 0.8947\]

    By comparing the \(z\) score to the grade chart, you find the proper rating is B.
